SIMPLE: ride
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ride
<hw>Ride</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Rode</conjf> <pr>(r⟦omac⟧d)</pr> (<conjf>Rid</conjf> [r⟦icr⟧d],
<mark>archaic</mark>); <pos>p. p.</pos> <conjf>Ridden</conjf>
<pr>(<?/)</pr> (<conjf>Rid</conjf>, <mark>archaic</mark>); <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Riding</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS.
<ets>r⟦imac⟧dan</ets>; akin to LG. <ets>riden</ets>, D.
<ets>rijden</ets>, G. <ets>reiten</ets>, OHG. <ets>r⟦imac⟧tan</ets>,
Icel. <ets>r⟦imac⟧⟦edh⟧a</ets>, Sw. <ets>rida</ets>, Dan.
<ets>ride</ets>; cf. L. <ets>raeda</ets> a carriage, which is from a
Celtic word. Cf. <er>Road</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be carried on
the back of an animal, as a horse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To-morrow, when ye <qex>riden</qex> by the way.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let your master <qex>ride</qex> on before, and do you gallop after
him.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be borne in a carriage; <as>as, to <ex>ride</ex>
in a coach, in a car, and the like</as>. See Synonym, below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The richest inhabitants exhibited their wealth, not by
<qex>riding</qex> in gilden carriages, but by walking the streets with
trains of servants.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be borne or in a fluid; to float; to
lie.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men once walked where ships at anchor <qex>ride</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be supported in motion; to rest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Strong as the exletree⟦br⟧
On which heaven <qex>rides</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>On whose foolish honesty⟦br⟧
My practices <qex>ride</qex> easy!</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To manage a horse, as an equestrian.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>rode</qex>, he fenced, he moved with graceful ease.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To support a rider, as a horse; to move under the
saddle; <as>as, a horse <ex>rides</ex> easy or hard, slow or
fast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To ride easy</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to lie at
anchor without violent pitching or straining at the cables.</cd> --
<col><b>To ride hard</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to pitch
violently.</cd> -- <col><b>To ride out</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To go
upon a military expedition.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Chaucer.</au>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To ride in the open air.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark> --
<col><b>To ride to hounds</b></col>, <cd>to ride behind, and near to,
the hounds in hunting.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Drive.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Ride</er>,
<er>Drive</er>. <xex>Ride</xex> originally meant (and is so used
throughout the English Bible) to be carried on horseback or in a vehicle
of any kind. At present in England, <xex>drive</xex> is the word applied
in most cases to progress in a carriage; as, a <xex>drive</xex> around
the park, etc.; while <xex>ride</xex> is appropriated to progress on a
horse. Johnson seems to sanction this distinction by giving ⟦ldquo⟧to
<xex>travel</xex> on horseback⟦rdquo⟧ as the leading sense of
<xex>ride</xex>; though he adds ⟦ldquo⟧to <xex>travel</xex> in a
vehicle⟦rdquo⟧ as a secondary sense. This latter use of the word still
occurs to some extent; as, the queen <xex>rides</xex> to Parliament in
her coach of state; to <xex>ride</xex> in an omnibus.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>⟦ldquo⟧Will you <qex>ride</qex> over or <qex>drive</qex>?⟦rdquo⟧
said Lord Willowby to his quest, after breakfast that morning.</q>
<rj><qau>W. Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ride</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Ride
<hw>Ride</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To sit on, so as to be
carried; <as>as, to <ex>ride</ex> a horse; to <ex>ride</ex> a
bicycle.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] rend up both rocks and hills, and <qex>ride</qex> the
air⟦br⟧
In whirlwind.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To manage insolently at will; to domineer
over.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The nobility could no longer endure to be <qex>ridden</qex> by
bakers, cobblers, and brewers.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To convey, as by riding; to make or do by
riding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Tue only men that safe can <qex>ride</qex>⟦br⟧
Mine errands on the Scottish side.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Surg.)</fld> <def>To overlap (each other); -- said
of bones or fractured fragments.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To ride a hobby</b></col>, <cd>to have some favorite
occupation or subject of talk.</cd> -- <col><b>To ride and
tie</b></col>, <cd>to take turn with another in labor and rest; -- from
the expedient adopted by two persons with one horse, one of whom
<xex>rides</xex> the animal a certain distance, and then <xex>ties</xex>
him for the use of the other, who is coming up on foot.</cd>
<au>Fielding.</au> -- <col><b>To ride down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>To ride over; to trample down in riding; to overthrow by riding
against; <as>as, <ex>to ride down</ex> an enemy</as></cd>. <sd>(b)</sd>
<fld>(Naut.)</fld> <cd>To bear down, as on a halyard when hoisting a
sail.</cd> -- <col><b>To ride out</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>to
keep safe afloat during (a storm) while riding at anchor or when hove to
on the open sea; <as>as, <ex>to ride out</ex> the gale</as>.</cd></cs>
<-- <col><b>to ride the lightning</b></col>, (Colloq.) <cd>to be
executed by electrocution in an electric chair.</cd> -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ride</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Ride
<hw>Ride</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of riding; an
excursion on horseback or in a vehicle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A saddle horse.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Wright.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A road or avenue cut in a wood, or through grounds,
to be used as a place for riding; a riding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rideau</ent>⟦br⟧
